Classifying Fetus Health from Cardiotocogram Measurements

Data Setup

# read in the data, select only the response variable and relevant features,
# and drop empty rows and duplicate observations
dat <- read_excel(paste0(path, "CTG.xls"), sheet = 3)
dat = dat[, c(7:17, 19:28, 40)]
dat = unique(dat[-c(1, 2128:2130), ])

# convert the categorical variables to factors
dat$Tendency = as.factor(dat$Tendency)
dat$NSP = factor(ifelse(dat$NSP == 1, "N", ifelse(dat$NSP == 2, "S", "P")),
                 levels = c("N", "S", "P"))

Exploratory Data Analysis

Descriptions of Features

feature description
LB baseline of the fetal heart rate in beats per minute
AC number of accelerations/second
FM number of fetal movements/second
UC number of uterine contractions/second
DL number of light decelerations/second
DS number of severe decelerations/second
DP number of prolonged decelerations/second
ASTV percentage of time with abnormal short term variability
MSTV mean value of short term variability
ALTV percentage of time with abnormal long term variability
MLTV mean value of long term variability
Width width of fetal heart rate histogram
Min minimum of fetal heart rate histogram
Max maximum of fetal heart rate histogram
Nmax number of fetal heart rate histogram peaks
Nzeros number of fetal heart rate histogram zeros
Mode fetal heart rate histogram mode
Mean fetal heart rate histogram mean
Median fetal heart rate histogram median
Variance fetal heart rate histogram variance
Tendency fetal heart rate histogram tendency

Distribution of the Response

N = Normal, S = Suspect, P = Pathological

Creating a Balanced Dataset

Partitioning the Data

# convert the Tendency feature into three dummy variables for model building
dat$TendencyLeft = ifelse(dat$Tendency == "-1", 1, 0)
dat$TendencySymmetric = ifelse(dat$Tendency == "0", 1, 0)
dat$TendencyRight = ifelse(dat$Tendency == "1", 1, 0)
dat = dat[, c(1:20, 23:25, 22)]

# partition the data into training and test sets
set.seed(1)
train.index = sample(nrow(dat), 0.7*nrow(dat))
train.data = dat[train.index, ]
test.data = dat[-train.index, ]

Perform Oversampling

Oversample the P class by generating 250 synthetic observations for a total of 375 (3x as many observations than the original training set). Oversample the S class by generating 171 synthetic observations, also for a total of 375. Undersample the N class.

set.seed(2)
overNS <- SMOTE(NSP ~ .,
                data.frame(train.data %>% filter(NSP != "P") %>% mutate(NSP = as.factor(as.character(NSP)))),
                perc.under = 219.5,
                perc.over = 84,
                k = 5)
overP <- SMOTE(NSP ~ .,
               data.frame(train.data %>% filter(NSP != "S") %>% mutate(NSP = as.factor(as.character(NSP)))),
               perc.under = 0,
               perc.over = 200,
               k = 5)
over <- bind_rows(overNS, overP)
rm(overNS, overP)
kable(table(over$NSP), col.names = c("Fetus Health", "Count"))
Fetus Health Count
N 388
S 388
P 396

Model Building

Neural Network

Oversampled Dataset

set.seed(3)
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
tune.grid <- expand.grid(size = seq(1, 23, 1),
                         decay = seq(0.1, 0.5, 0.1))
no.print <- capture.output(
  overNN <- train(NSP ~ ., data = over, method = "nnet",
                  preProc = c("center", "scale"),
                  trControl = train_control, tuneGrid = tune.grid)
)
overNN$bestTune
##     size decay
## 106   22   0.1
pred.test = predict(overNN, test.data)
confusionMatrix(pred.test, test.data$NSP)

Random Forest Models

Oversampled Dataset

set.seed(5)
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
overRF <- train(NSP ~ ., data = over, method = "rf",
                trControl = train_control, tuneGrid = data.frame(mtry = 1:12))
overRF$bestTune
##    mtry
## 12   12
pred.test = predict(overRF$finalModel, test.data, type = 'class')
confusionMatrix(pred.test, test.data$NSP)
